@flexiarg relationship-coherence/cook-as-care
@title Feed the Depleted One
@sigils [🍲/餵]
@keywords cooking, food, provisioning, care, nourishment, reciprocity, imbalance
@audience correspondents who care through food
@references [relationship-coherence/capacity-honoring relationship-coherence/base-camp]
@references-extra ["Instance of origin: 2026-05-26 — Joe offers to bring dinner ('3 big packets of sautée mushrooms... a mushroom pasta could go over well?'). Recurs as a standing form of care and a tracked imbalance: 2026-06-02 Julia, 'Are you sure? Lately I seem to always make you bring dinner!'; 2026-06-13 'If you could bring pasta... and mushrooms I have an idea!'"]
@tone practical
@style pattern

! conclusion: When one of you is depleted or out of food, source, make, or bring dinner — feeding the other is a direct, embodied form of care; let the receiver name any imbalance.

  + context: Depletion is the pair's chronic condition (see relationship-coherence/capacity-honoring), and food is a recurring answer to it — groceries fetched en route, mushroom pasta cooked, dinner carried to whoever is flagging.

  + IF:
    the other is tired, unwell, or without groceries, and a shared meal would restore more than it costs.

  + HOWEVER:
    one-directional feeding can quietly become an imbalance ('I always make you bring dinner'); care through food stays healthy when the imbalance can be named and, over time, reciprocated.

  + THEN:
    offer to provision and cook; and when the giving runs one way, let the receiver flag it and find a way to give back.

  + BECAUSE:
    feeding someone is capacity-honoring made tangible — it meets the body's depletion directly; keeping it reciprocal keeps it care rather than debt.

  + NEXT-STEPS:
    - Pair with relationship-coherence/base-camp (the hub is where the cooking happens) and relationship-coherence/capacity-honoring (food is a concrete answer to depletion).
